Being an introverted creative and working independently while placing a high value on one's privacy should not be a contradiction, but it often is. Most online sources and coaches advise working with the (evil) tech giants and behaving extrovertedly. Promote yourself here, follow the algorithm, show your personality. Get a blue checkmark on that service, be reachable 24/7, answer inquiries with a video of yourself, respond immediately. Video, video, video.
1/3
For me, it is a year of changes.
I don't want to feed the tech giants with money, data, and my energy. Or coaches who have their own extroverted solutions and push them on everyone. I'm searching for new ways to run a business, while at the same time fighting against my long-held belief that you have to do things a certain way to be successful.
Wish me luck!
The first steps have already been taken.
I have canceled my FB account, removed all Meta and Pinterest trackers from my website, and deleted my private WhatsApp account.
Yesterday I also removed Google Analytics, the last external tracker, from my website and feel good about it.
Recently, I subscribed to a European CRM to have better DSGVO support, and I will be moving my business there in the next few weeks.
I have transferred my MX account to Proton and now have full SPF, DKIM, and DMARC without having to pay Google for standard email validation.
3/3
